===Noun===
{{en-noun|accurac|ies}}

# The state of being [[accurate]]; freedom from [[mistakes]], this [[exemption]] arising from [[carefulness]]; [[exactness]]; [[nicety]]; [[correctness]]
#: ''The value of testimony depends on its '''accuracy'''.''
#* {{quote-book|author=[[W:Thomas Reid|Thomas Reid]]|passage=Its professed end [of logic], is to teach men to think, to judge, and to reason, with precision and '''accuracy'''.|title=Essays on the Powers of the Human Mind|year=1827|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=7fENAAAAYAAJ}}
#* {{quote-book|passage=The efficiency of the instrument will also depend upon the '''accuracy''' with which the piston fits the bottom and sides of the barrel. When the piston is depressed to the bottom, it is considered in theory to be in absolute contact, so as to exclude every particle of air from the space between it and the bottom.|title=Popular Lectures on Science and Art|author=Dionysius Lardner|year=1856|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BkUPAAAAYAAJ}}
# Exact conformity to truth, or to a rule or model; degree of conformity of a measure to a true or standard value.

